-[woman] Good shot!

271
00:14:01,800 --> 00:14:03,842
[cheers, applause continue]

272
00:14:05,345 --> 00:14:07,430
[dramatic music]

273
00:14:12,851 --> 00:14:16,439
-Have I got a big nose, Mum?
-Oh, stop thinking about sex.

274
00:14:16,481 --> 00:14:18,817
-I wasn't!
-You're always on about it.

275
00:14:18,857 --> 00:14:20,401
Morning, noon and night.

276
00:14:20,443 --> 00:14:23,112
"Will the girls like this,
will the girls like that?

277
00:14:23,154 --> 00:14:26,157
Is it too big,
is it too small?"

278
00:14:26,199 --> 00:14:28,159
[indistinct chattering]

279
00:14:28,201 --> 00:14:31,954
-Alms for a leper.
-Alms for a leper.

280
00:14:31,996 --> 00:14:34,749
Alms for an ex-leper.

281
00:14:34,791 --> 00:14:37,084
Bloody donkey-owners,
all the same, ain't they?

282
00:14:37,126 --> 00:14:38,837
Never have any change.

283
00:14:38,878 --> 00:14:40,839
Oh, here's a touch.

284
00:14:40,880 --> 00:14:42,465
Spare a talent
for an old ex-leper?

285
00:14:42,507 --> 00:14:43,966
Buzz off!

286
00:14:44,008 --> 00:14:45,719
Spare a talent
for an old ex-leper?

287
00:14:45,760 --> 00:14:48,388
A talent? That's more than
he earns in a month.

288
00:14:48,429 --> 00:14:50,306
-Half a talent then?
-No, go away.

289
00:14:50,348 --> 00:14:52,183
-Come on, big nose,
let's haggle.
-What?

290
00:14:52,225 --> 00:14:54,477
All right, cut the haggling,
say you open at one shekel,

291
00:14:54,519 --> 00:14:56,813
I start at 2000,
we close about 1800.

292
00:14:56,855 --> 00:14:57,980
-No.
-Seventeen fifty?

293
00:14:58,022 --> 00:15:00,233
-Go away!
-Seventeen forty?

294
00:15:00,274 --> 00:15:01,609
Will you leave him alone!

295
00:15:01,651 --> 00:15:02,694
All right.
Two shekels, just two.

296
00:15:02,736 --> 00:15:04,028
Is this fun, eh?

297
00:15:04,070 --> 00:15:05,905
Look,
he's not giving you any money.

298
00:15:05,946 --> 00:15:07,490
Now piss off!

299
00:15:11,661 --> 00:15:14,163
All right, final offer,
half a shekel for an ex-leper?

300
00:15:14,205 --> 00:15:16,207
Did you say "ex-leper"?

301
00:15:16,249 --> 00:15:18,793
That's right, sir, 16 years
behind a bell and proud of it,
sir.

302
00:15:18,835 --> 00:15:21,421
-Well, what happened?
-I was cured, sir.

303
00:15:21,462 --> 00:15:23,214
-Cured?
-Yes, a bloody miracle, sir.

304
00:15:23,256 --> 00:15:25,383
-God bless you.
-Who cured you?

305
00:15:25,425 --> 00:15:26,967
Jesus did, sir.

306
00:15:27,009 --> 00:15:28,969
I was hopping along,
minding my own business.

307
00:15:29,011 --> 00:15:31,305
All of a sudden,
up he comes, cures me.

308
00:15:31,347 --> 00:15:33,057
One minute
I'm a leper with a trade,

309
00:15:33,099 --> 00:15:34,517
next minute
my livelihood's gone.

310
00:15:34,559 --> 00:15:36,143
Not so much as a
"by your leave."

311
00:15:36,185 --> 00:15:38,688
"You're cured, mate."
Bloody do-gooder.

312
00:15:38,730 --> 00:15:40,732
Well, why don't you
go and tell him

313
00:15:40,774 --> 00:15:42,483
that you want to be
a leper again?

314
00:15:42,525 --> 00:15:44,736
I could do that, sir.
Yeah, I could that, I suppose.

315
00:15:44,778 --> 00:15:46,571
What I was thinking was gonna
ask him if he'd make me

316
00:15:46,613 --> 00:15:48,573
a bit lame in one leg
during the middle of the week.

317
00:15:48,615 --> 00:15:50,658
You know, something beggable,
but not leprosy,

318
00:15:50,700 --> 00:15:52,744
which is a pain in the ass,
to be blunt.
Excuse my French, sir.

319
00:15:52,786 --> 00:15:56,790
Brian.
Come and clean your room out.

320
00:15:56,831 --> 00:15:58,499
-There you are.
-Thank you, sir. Thank...

321
00:15:58,541 --> 00:16:01,711
Half a denarii
for me bloody life story?

322
00:16:01,753 --> 00:16:03,755
There's no pleasing
some people.

323
00:16:03,797 --> 00:16:05,757
That's just what
Jesus said, sir.

324
00:16:17,811 --> 00:16:20,855
-Oh!
-Good afternoon.

325
00:16:20,897 --> 00:16:22,482
Oh, uh,
hello, officer.

326
00:16:22,523 --> 00:16:27,403
Uh... I'll be with you in a few
moments, all right, dear?

327
00:16:27,445 --> 00:16:28,863
What's he doing here?

328
00:16:28,905 --> 00:16:30,949
Don't start that, Brian.
Go clean your room out.

329
00:16:30,990 --> 00:16:32,408
Bloody Romans.

330
00:16:32,450 --> 00:16:34,535
Now, look, Brian,
if it wasn't for them,

331
00:16:34,577 --> 00:16:37,413
we wouldn't have all this.
And don't you forget it.

332
00:16:37,455 --> 00:16:39,415
We don't owe
the Romans anything, Mum.

333
00:16:39,457 --> 00:16:42,168
Well, that's not entirely true,
is it, Brian?

334
00:16:42,209 --> 00:16:43,920
What do you mean?

335
00:16:43,962 --> 00:16:46,422
Well, you know when you
were asking me about your, uh--

336
00:16:46,464 --> 00:16:47,966
-My nose?
-Yes.

337
00:16:48,007 --> 00:16:50,510
Well, there's a reason
it's like it is, Brian.

338
00:16:50,551 --> 00:16:52,428
What is it?

339
00:16:52,470 --> 00:16:56,933
-Well, I suppose I should have
told you a long time ago, but...
-What?

340
00:16:56,975 --> 00:16:58,476
Well, Brian...

341
00:16:59,978 --> 00:17:02,146
your father
isn't Mr. Cohen.

342
00:17:02,188 --> 00:17:04,774
-I never thought he was.
-Now, none of your cheek!

343
00:17:04,816 --> 00:17:07,485
He was a Roman, Brian.

344
00:17:07,527 --> 00:17:10,655
He was a centurion
in the Roman army.

345
00:17:10,697 --> 00:17:12,991
You mean you were raped?!

346
00:17:13,032 --> 00:17:15,034
Well, at first, yes.

347
00:17:15,075 --> 00:17:16,369
Who was it?

348
00:17:16,410 --> 00:17:19,079
Naughtius Maximus
his name was. Hmm.

349
00:17:19,121 --> 00:17:21,499
Promised me the known world,
he did.

350
00:17:21,541 --> 00:17:24,711
I was to be taken to Rome,
house by the Forum,

351
00:17:24,752 --> 00:17:26,546
slaves, asses' milk,

352
00:17:26,587 --> 00:17:29,131
as much gold
as I could eat.

353
00:17:29,173 --> 00:17:31,676
Then he,
having his way with me he had,

354
00:17:31,718 --> 00:17:34,136
boom, like a rat
out of an aqueduct.

355
00:17:34,178 --> 00:17:35,680
The bastard!

356
00:17:35,722 --> 00:17:38,474
Yes, and next time you go on
about the "bloody Romans"

357
00:17:38,516 --> 00:17:40,434
don't forget
you're one of them.

358
00:17:40,476 --> 00:17:42,020
I'm not a Roman, Mum.

359
00:17:42,061 --> 00:17:43,396
And I never will be.

360
00:17:43,437 --> 00:17:46,774
I'm a kike, a yid,
a hebe, a hooknose.

361
00:17:46,816 --> 00:17:48,026
I'm kosher, Mum.

362
00:17:48,067 --> 00:17:51,779
I'm a Red Sea pedestrian
and proud of it!

363
00:17:52,864 --> 00:17:54,365
[door slams]

364
00:17:54,407 --> 00:17:55,825
[chuckles]

365
00:17:55,867 --> 00:17:58,494
Sex, sex, sex, that's all
they think about, huh?

366
00:17:58,536 --> 00:18:01,039
Well, how are you then, officer?

367
00:18:02,122 --> 00:18:05,710
[plays fanfare]

368
00:18:11,007 --> 00:18:12,717
[light applause]

369
00:18:12,759 --> 00:18:15,261
[quiet chattering]

370
00:18:18,765 --> 00:18:21,017
[announcer]
Ladies and gentlemen,

371
00:18:21,059 --> 00:18:24,812
the next contest is between

372
00:18:24,854 --> 00:18:30,484
